Overview

This project uses learning models to predict how well participants with wearable fit tech performed exercises. The aim is to use these performance data to improve data quality for both user and future applications of wearable tech.

Data readings were taken from 10 reps for five different movements, one correct (A) and four incorrect (B-D):
  * A: according to instructions (Class A)
* B: throwing the elbows to the front (Class B)
* C: lifting the weight halfway (Class C)
* D: lowering the weight halfway (Class D)
* E: throwing the hips to the front (Class E)

A random forest machine learning algorithm was applied to test how well the training data could predict the four incorrect exercise movements in the test data. The model tested Total acceleration of the forearm and Total acceleration of the arm variables for one user.

Training model

First, the training model was built from the training dataset, then each of the five movements for a user were plotted over time.

Testing data

These metrics were then tested against the testing data to determine how well the random forest model performed in predicting the outcomes. By comparing the results over time against the training data, we can see where the model attempts to predict each movement (A to E). The green dots represent the number of instances where the training model accurately predicted the testing data within 95%.

The trained model was then tested against the Total acceleration of the forearm and Total acceleration of the arm testing data to show performance for each class of movement.

Total acceleration of the forearm

Total acceleration of the arm

Conclusion

The training model adequately captured performace in the testing data for three of the four incorrect fitness movements (B, D, and E) with a reported accuracy of 82%.
